{:proof/problem-id "apm-a93J05", :proof/classification :partial, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (explicitly talks about entire, doubly periodic functions with periods 1 and i) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the Lean target concludes constancy only after the hypotheses) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (this Liouville-style theorem stands on its own) · notes: Showing boundedness via the fundamental parallelogram plus Liouville is exactly the rigour we need before coding.\n\n```\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Show that a doubly periodic entire function with lattice periods 1 and i must be constant.\"\n :terms [{:name \"doubly periodic function\"\n          :meaning \"f(z+n+im)=f(z) for all integers n,m.\"\n          :needed-because \"Allows us to reduce the study of f to one fundamental parallelogram.\"}\n         {:name \"fundamental parallelogram\"\n          :meaning \"The compact set P={x+iy : 0≤x≤1, 0≤y≤1}.\"\n          :needed-because \"f’s values on all of ℂ are determined by its restriction to P.\"}\n         {:name \"Liouville’s theorem\"\n          :meaning \"A bounded entire function is constant.\"\n          :needed-because \"Once we show periodicity forces boundedness, Liouville finishes the proof.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"Periodicity implies boundedness via compact fundamental domain\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 decomposition of ℂ into translates of [0,1]×[0,1]\"\n             :why-this-now \"Map any z back into the fundamental parallelogram and use continuity on a compact set to bound f globally.\"\n             :lean-target \"periodic_entire_bounded\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Need lemmas about periodic functions and compactness of rectangles; standard in mathlib.\"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"Liouville’s theorem\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 recognition that bounded entire ⇒ constant\"\n             :why-this-now \"Apply Liouville once boundedness is obtained.\"\n             :lean-target \"doubly_periodic_entire_constant\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Liouville is in mathlib; we only need to invoke it.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"Any entire function that is periodic with respect to the lattice Z + iZ is constant.\"\n             :formal-name \"doubly_periodic_entire_constant\"\n             :formal-target \"∀ f : ℂ → ℂ, AnalyticOn f ⊤ ∧ (∀ z n m : ℤ, f z = f (z + (n : ℂ) + (m : ℂ) * I)) → ∀ z w, f z = f w\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"Encodes exactly the prelim statement: entire + 1, i periods ⇒ constant.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"doubly_periodic_entire_constant\"\n              :formal-statement \"∀ f : ℂ → ℂ, AnalyticOn f ⊤ ∧ (∀ z n m : ℤ, f z = f (z + (n : ℂ) + (m : ℂ) * I)) → ∀ z w, f z = f w\"\n              :informal-clause \"Main claim that doubly periodic entire functions are constant.\"\n              :role :main-theorem}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.** Single-period entire functions like \\(e^z\\) are anything but constant, so it’s easy to miss that having *two* independent periods changes everything. The prelim’s trap is trying to invoke Liouville’s theorem without first proving the function is bounded; that boundedness only comes from the fact that a rank-two lattice tiles the plane by compact fundamental domains.\n\n**Key insight.** Reduce to one fundamental parallelogram (say \\(P=\\{x+iy:0\\le x,y\\le 1\\}\\)). Periodicity shows every value of \\(f\\) is a translate of a value on \\(P\\). Since \\(f\\) is continuous and \\(P\\) is compact, \\(|f|\\) attains a maximum on \\(P\\), which then bounds \\(|f|\\) everywhere. A bounded entire function is constant by Liouville.\n\n**Complete proof.** Let \\(f:\\mathbf{C}\\to\\mathbf{C}\\) be entire with \\(f(z+n+im)=f(z)\\) for all \\(n,m\\in\\mathbf{Z}\\). For any \\(z=x+iy\\) choose integers \\(n=\\lfloor x\\rfloor\\) and \\(m=\\lfloor y\\rfloor\\); then \\(w=z-(n+im)\\) lies in \\(P\\). Periodicity gives \\(|f(z)|=|f(w)|\\le M\\), where \\(M=\\max_{u\\in P}|f(u)|<\\infty\\) because \\(f\\) is continuous on compact \\(P\\). Hence \\(f\\) is bounded on \\(\\mathbf{C}\\). By Liouville’s theorem a bounded entire function is constant, so \\(f\\) is constant on \\(\\mathbf{C}\\). □\n\n**Lean 4 formalization.**  \n- Target theorem: `doubly_periodic_entire_constant` (recorded in `formal-alignment.edn`) stating that an entire function invariant under shifts by `n + m*I` is constant.  \n- Plan (`proof-plan.edn`): prove `periodic_entire_bounded` by restricting to the compact rectangle, then invoke Liouville.  \n- Implementation status (Stage 3 “in progress”): remaining Lean work is to formalize the lattice reduction using `Real.floor`, show the fundamental domain is compact, bound `‖f z‖` via periodicity, and call Mathlib’s Liouville lemma (`Complex.isometry_subsingleton_of_isBounded`). No `sorry`s have been introduced yet; code is still to be written in `Main.lean`.\n\n**What connects.** This argument is the exam-friendly form of a general fact: any holomorphic map from a compact complex manifold (like the torus \\(\\mathbf{C}/(\\mathbf{Z}+\\tau \\mathbf{Z})\\)) to \\(\\mathbf{C}\\) (or \\(\\mathbf{P}^1\\) without poles) must be constant. The “bounded on a fundamental domain + Liouville” maneuver is a standard exam trick; the same approach shows that entire functions with any two linearly independent periods are constant, and it’s one step away from the theory of elliptic (meromorphic, doubly periodic) functions. Artifacts updated: `execute.md` now houses the full write-up, `proof-plan.edn` the structured plan, `formal-alignment.edn` the Lean target, and `changelog.edn` records Stage 1/2 completion with Stage 3 still pending.", :proof/extraction {:phases {}, :dependency-graph nil, :arse-questions nil, :classification :partial, :phase-count 0, :dep-graph-count 0, :arse-count 0}, :proof/frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A93J05/Apm_v2_a93J05_1775002708409", :frame/id "apm-v2-a93J05-1775002708409", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T00:18:28.432547Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.A93J05.Apm_v2_a93J05_1775002708409", :proof/problem-id "a93J05", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :frame/workspace-root "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a93J05/apm-v2-a93J05-1775002708409", :artifacts {:proof-plan "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a93J05/apm-v2-a93J05-1775002708409/proof-plan.edn", :formal-alignment "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a93J05/apm-v2-a93J05-1775002708409/formal-alignment.edn", :changelog "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a93J05/apm-v2-a93J05-1775002708409/changelog.edn", :execute-notes "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a93J05/apm-v2-a93J05-1775002708409/execute.md", :workspace-readme "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a93J05/apm-v2-a93J05-1775002708409/README.md", :workspace-metadata "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a93J05/apm-v2-a93J05-1775002708409/workspace.json", :lean-main "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A93J05/Apm_v2_a93J05_1775002708409/Main.lean", :lean-scratch "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A93J05/Apm_v2_a93J05_1775002708409/Scratch.lean"}}, :proof/artifacts ["/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A93J05/Apm_v2_a93J05_1775002708409/Main.lean" "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A93J05/Apm_v2_a93J05_1775002708409/Scratch.lean"], :proof/elapsed-ms 81587}